and CBS]

3
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:12,000
I liked how when they sang
"Everything got really smooth."

4
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:14,000
Oh, wait, wait, wait.
Hold on.

5
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:26,000
Dianne, I got
an extra one.

6
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Can you save it
so I can give it to Julia?

7
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Oh, yeah. Good idea.

8
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:31,000
She'll like that.

9
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Yeah.

10
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:33,000
Let's get a cab.

11
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:34,000
Oh.

12
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Evening.
Hi.

13
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Hi. You free?

14
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:37,000
Yes, ma'am.

15
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:42,000
( horn blares, tires squeal )

16
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:46,000
Amy!

17
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:04,000
MAN ( over radio):
Aphrodite, Aphrodite.

18
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:05,000
This is the marine operator

19
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:09,000
for Captain Mark McCune.

20
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:11,000
McCune aboard the Aphrodite.

21
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:12,000
I've got the emergency room

22
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
at San Francisco
County Hospital.

23
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
They're asking if you know
a Dianne Parker.

24
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:49,000
Taxi!

25
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:10,000
MARK:
Hello? Excuse me.

26
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:15,000
Hello?

27
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:17,000
Hello.
Hi.

28
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
Hi. I'm looking
for Parker.

29
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Oh, it's Dianne. Dianne Parker.

30
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:25,000
Can I help you?

31
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:29,000
Uh, yeah. You have a playhouse
for my brother, Dr. McCune.

32
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:30,000
Oh, yeah.

33
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:33,000
So just tell David
to call me.

34
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:36,000
I'll come by his office
and put it together for him.

35
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,000
What's wrong with now?

36
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:39,000
I'll help you.

37
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:41,000
Then you can say thanks;
I'll say, "Forget about it.

38
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:42,000
Have dinner with me
on my yacht."

39
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:44,000
You'll say,
"Sure. Why not?"

40
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:46,000
See? I give you the easy part.

41
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,000
I say, "Sure. Why not?"

42
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:49,000
You don't even know me.

43
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:51,000
I know you're strong
and you work hard

44
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,000
and you're not afraid
to get your clothes dirty.

45
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:57,000
You're not dating my brother,
are you?

46
00:03:57,000 --> 00:03:59,000
No. we're friends.

47
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:03,000
He can chaperone
if you're scared.

48
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:12,000
( knock on door )

49
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
Sailor boy's unloading
the playhouse.

50
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,000
Okay.

51
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,000
That girl's come, too.

52
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,000
Dianne's here?

53
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:29,000
MARK:
It's very simple.

54
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Watch me. Watch me.

55
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:31,000
Like this, all right?

56
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:33,000
Wait, wait, wait.

57
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:34,000
Then fold it back.

58
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,000
Come on. Come on.
Keep up with the master.

59
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:38,000
Here, use a clean one.

60
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:39,000
No. No do-overs.

61
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:41,000
Just fold it
back like this.

62
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,000
Where did you learn
how to do this?

63
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:45,000
Some old guy
in a Chinese
opium den.

64
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:46,000
You've been to China?

65
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:48,000
I've been everywhere.

66
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Ooh, Tales from the sea.

67
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:51,000
Take him with a grain of salt,
please.

68
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:53,000
MARK:
All right.

69
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
Miss Piggot, my
seventh-grade art
teacher had me

70
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:56,000
stay after school
and make 50 of these.

71
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:58,000
It was my punishment.

72
00:04:58,000 --> 00:04:59,000
For what?

73
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:00,000
You don't want to know.

74
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:01,000
You won't like me anymore.

75
00:05:01,000 --> 00:05:03,000
Who says I like you now?

76
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:04,000
Come on. You tell me.

77
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:05,000
He was too busy

78
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:07,000
running for student
council president.

79
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:08,000
He doesn't remember.

80
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:10,000
Treasurer.
I was running for treasurer.

81
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:13,000
Well, I was running for my life.

82
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:15,000
You got sauce on your chin.

83
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,000
Thanks.

84
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:19,000
There you go.

85
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:21,000
( tittering )

86
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:23,000
MARK:
Thank you.

87
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:26,000
Sure.

88
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:27,000
( laughs )

89
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:12,000
MARK:
That's Orion.

90
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:16,000
Canis Major.

91
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:18,000
Taurus.

92
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:23,000
My mother, she painted them
on her bedroom ceiling.

93
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,000
You never talk
about her.

94
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,000
Nothing to talk about.

95
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:29,000
( crickets chirping )

96
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:36,000
( sighs )

97
00:06:37,000 --> 00:06:42,000
It took two years.

98
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:44,000
I hated the hospital.

99
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:47,000
I... stopped going.

100
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:50,000
David, he was,
he was the hero.

101
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:52,000
He held her hand.

102
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:54,000
You were 12.

103
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:58,000
No, he kept asking me
to come with him.

104
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:02,000
Said she wanted to see me.

105
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:06,000
Say good-bye.

106
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:09,000
I don't beat
myself up about it.

107
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:22,000
Mothers aren't
supposed to die.

108
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:25,000
You had every right
to be angry.

109
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:28,000
She understood.

110
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:30,000
She knew you loved her.

111
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:38,000
How do you do that?

112
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:43,000
Make me feel like
you've known me
all my life?

113
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:46,000
Maybe we're soul mates.

114
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:49,000
You make
everything perfect.

115
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:51,000
I mean it.

116
00:07:51,000 --> 00:07:54,000
I need you.

117
00:07:56,000 --> 00:07:57,000
I love you.

118
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:27,000
( car horn honking )

119
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:32,000
David! David!

120
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:33,000
She said yes!

121
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:36,000
She said yes!

122
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:37,000
We're getting married!

123
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:42,000
Come on.
Say something, David.

124
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,000
Come on.
Say something.

125
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,000
Congratulations.

126
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:46,000
He's jealous.

127
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:47,000
No. No, that's great.
I didn't...

128
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:48,000
Congratulations.

129
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,000
Thank you.

130
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:50,000
That's wonderful.

131
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:52,000
Mmm... mmm!

132
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:56,000
Oh, everyone in the world
is jealous of me right now.

133
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:53,000
Good morning,
Mr. Fisherman.

134
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:55,000
Good morning,
Mrs. Fisherman.

135
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,000
Oh, don't get lost
out there, okay?

136
00:09:57,000 --> 00:09:59,000
I can't get lost.

137
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:01,000
What do you think
the stars are for?

138
00:10:01,000 --> 00:10:05,000
God never figured
we'd invent a compass.

139
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:07,000
If you need directions,
just follow the stars.

140
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:11,000
Besides, I'll always
come home to you.

141
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:14,000
Me and the kids?

142
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:16,000
Kids?

143
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:21,000
Well, one, for starters.

144
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:24,000
Woo!

145
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:25,000
Come here!

146
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:27,000
Oh!

147
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:29,000
( laughing )

148
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:31,000
Wow!

149
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:33,000
This... mmm!

150
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:38,000
Hi.

151
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:41,000
Hi. You seen my mom?

152
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:43,000
She's over in the stacks.

153
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:56,000
What are you
doing here?

154
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:57,000
( whispering )

155
00:10:57,000 --> 00:10:58,000
What?

156
00:10:58,000 --> 00:10:59,000
No!

157
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:00,000
( laughing )

158
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:02,000
Oh, my!

159
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,000
You're lucky you're over
morning sickness.

160
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:10,000
So did you have morning
sickness with me?

161
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:11,000
Morning, afternoon
and evening.

162
00:11:11,000 --> 00:11:13,000
You must be
having a boy.

163
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:14,000
Old wives tale.

164
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:15,000
You going to eat this?

165
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:17,000
No. I think you are.

166
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:18,000
Well...

167
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:21,000
how much weight
did you gain?

168
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:23,000
Oh, when you start running
after Mark Jr

169
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:24,000
it'll melt right off you.

170
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:26,000
No. If we have a boy

171
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:28,000
we're naming
him after Dad.

172
00:11:28,000 --> 00:11:29,000
You are?
Mm-hmm.

173
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:31,000
Well, thank you, sweetheart.

174
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:33,000
He'd like that.

175
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:36,000
I'm sorry.

176
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:37,000
I didn't mean
to make you sad.

177
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:38,000
Oh, no.

178
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:41,000
I was just remembering
when you were born.

179
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:44,000
I held you in my arms

180
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:47,000
and suddenly this wave
of terror came over me.

181
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:48,000
( chuckles )

182
00:11:48,000 --> 00:11:51,000
Here I was holding
this complete stranger.

183
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:53,000
How much should I feed you?

184
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:54,000
What if you wouldn't
stop crying?

185
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:58,000
Uh, suppose you hated me?

186
00:11:58,000 --> 00:12:02,000
Your dad came over to me
and he said... bless his heart...

187
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:05,000
"Hannah, give her to me."

188
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:07,000
And suddenly I knew
I didn't want to let you go.

189
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:10,000
You were mine.

190
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:14,000
We have a lot of books
about motherhood at the library

191
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:17,000
but none of them can prepare you
for that moment...

192
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:21,000
when you give your heart
to your child.

193
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:23,000
( gasps )

194
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:24,000
Oh!

195
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:25,000
( laughs )

196
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:27,000
What is it?

197
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:29,000
He kicked.
He kicked.

198
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:30,000
What?

199
00:12:30,000 --> 00:12:31,000
Oh, my!

200
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:34,000
I think he's going
to be a football player.

201
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:37,000
Just now. That was
the first kick.

202
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:38,000
Well, maybe

203
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:40,000
soccer, at least.

204
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:41,000
( laughing )

205
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:55,000
Please, don't cry,
okay?

206
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:58,000
It's going
to be okay.

207
00:12:58,000 --> 00:12:59,000
We'll figure it out.

208
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:01,000
It'll be okay.

209
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:03,000
It's not going
to be okay.

210
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:08,000
( crying )

211
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:13,000
Okay.

212
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:15,000
Listen...

213
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:22,000
Dianne, we'll...
we'll have a baby.

214
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:24,000
We'll have lots
of babies.

215
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:25,000
Just not now.

216
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:27,000
I want this baby.

217
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:30,000
Did you not understand
what Dr. Ellis was saying?

218
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:32,000
I don't care.

219
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:34,000
A baby who can't
walk or talk.

220
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:38,000
A baby who's
going to die.

221
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:40,000
Listen to me.

222
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:42,000
Dianne...

223
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:45,000
I can't deal with this.

224
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:09,000
Hey.

225
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:15,000
Genetic abnormalities.

226
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:17,000
Neurological damage.

227
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:20,000
Here, you went
to med school.

228
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:29,000
Did you take
a second test?

229
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:31,000
You're looking
at it.

230
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:38,000
Sorry.

231
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:40,000
How's Dianne?

232
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:44,000
She wants to have this baby.

233
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:46,000
You have to help me.

234
00:14:46,000 --> 00:14:47,000
Explain it to her.

235
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:49,000
Tell her that it's
not fair to the baby.

236
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:51,000
This is between you and her.

237
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:52,000
You're a doctor.
She'll listen to you.

238
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:55,000
Mark, I cannot tell someone
to terminate a pregnancy.

239
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:57,000
Forget your hypocritical oaths
and ethics.

240
00:14:57,000 --> 00:14:59,000
What if this was your baby?

241
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:01,000
Come on, David, be honest.

242
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:07,000
I don't know.

243
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:10,000
You know what you would do.

244
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:34,000
Anybody home?

245
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:36,000
Mark?

246
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:41,000
Dianne?

247
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:44,000
Mark's not here.

248
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:48,000
He left last night.

249
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:52,000
He'll be back.

250
00:15:55,000 --> 00:15:57,000
He's scared.

251
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:02,000
I'm scared, too.

252
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:03,000
He showed me
the test results.

253
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:06,000
I made some calls.

254
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:12,000
The spine and the nervous system
are damaged.

255
00:16:12,000 --> 00:16:15,000
There's fluid in the brain.

256
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:18,000
Your baby won't walk
or have normal speech.

257
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:34,000
If the heart and lungs
don't develop

258
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:37,000
they won't support
the body's growth.

259
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:39,000
This research expert
I spoke to said

260
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:43,000
he's seen cases like this
survive up to six years.

261
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:45,000
Don't tell me
not to have her.

262
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:46,000
I won't.

263
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:49,000
I mean, that's not
why I'm here.

264
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:52,000
She'll probably need
to undergo some surgery.

265
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:53,000
She'll need good care.

266
00:16:56,000 --> 00:16:59,000
I'll be her doctor
if you want.

267
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:06,000
Will she be in pain?

268
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:09,000
I'll help you.

269
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:13,000
I'll help you take care of her
if you want to do this.

270
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:23,000
Mark!

271
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:24,000
Dianne!

272
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:25,000
Dianne!

273
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:27,000
Grab my hand!

274
00:17:28,000 --> 00:17:30,000
Mark!

275
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:35,000
Dianne!

276
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:46,000
( voice echoing ):
Help!

277
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:49,000
( child crying )

278
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:56,000
Julia, I'm coming.

279
00:17:56,000 --> 00:17:58,000
I'm coming.

280
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:02,000
What is it, sweetie?

281
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:03,000
Oh, what is it?

282
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:05,000
Does it hurt?

283
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:07,000
Do you have a cramp?

284
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:10,000
Do you want me to rub it?

285
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:12,000
You want me
to rub your tummy?

286
00:18:12,000 --> 00:18:13,000
Oh, shh, shh.

287
00:18:13,000 --> 00:18:15,000
I know, I know.

288
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,000
Did you have a bad dream?

289
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:20,000
Oh, I know, I know.

290
00:18:20,000 --> 00:18:25,000
( clock chimes three times )

291
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:28,000
Is Julia all right?

292
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:30,000
Oh, yeah, she's fine.

293
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:33,000
Sweetheart,
you look terrible.

294
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:35,000
Go back to bed.

295
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:37,000
You're sick?

296
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:39,000
No. I just had
a bad dream.

297
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:41,000
Maybe Julia
had one, too.

298
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:44,000
I hate when
she's scared.

299
00:18:44,000 --> 00:18:47,000
I don't know
how to tell her
it's just a dream.

300
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:50,000
Oh, she knows.

301
00:18:50,000 --> 00:18:51,000
I dreamt about Mark.

302
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:54,000
He was drowning;
I couldn't save him.

303
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:55,000
Good.

304
00:18:55,000 --> 00:18:58,000
Forgive us our trespasses, Mom.

305
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:00,000
I forgave that
louse years ago.

306
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:02,000
I'm not the one
having nightmares.

307
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:05,000
You can't help what you dream.

308
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:07,000
Forgive and you'll forget.

309
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:09,000
Five years is a long time

310
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:12,000
to hold out hope
for an ex-husband.

311
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:14,000
Or carry a grudge.

312
00:19:14,000 --> 00:19:15,000
Or both.

313
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:17,000
Six. Six years
in August.

314
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:18,000
Yeah, but who's counting?

315
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:20,000
Not Mark.

316
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:21,000
He still sends you

317
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:22,000
a check every month.

318
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:24,000
Yeah, but that's
because he knows

319
00:19:24,000 --> 00:19:25,000
I'm going to send it right back.

320
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:27,000
It's his conscience cleaner.

321
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:28,000
It's his opening gambit

322
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:30,000
and you keep
the conversation going.

323
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:32,000
Why don't you
just rip it up

324
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:34,000
instead of mailing it
back to him?

325
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:36,000
You're right.

326
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:39,000
Next time I will.

327
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:41,000
( toy piano tinkling )

328
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:43,000
JULIA:
Ma...

329
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:50,000
DIANNE:
I think Grandma has one
of these somewhere.

330
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:53,000
We haven't seen it
in a while, have we?

331
00:19:56,000 --> 00:19:59,000
That's red...

332
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:02,000
and maybe that one's...

333
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:05,000
that's more
brown than red.

334
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:06,000
And orange.

335
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:07,000
Ma...

336
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:09,000
What's she got?

337
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:10,000
Nothing.

338
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:12,000
We're just here
for a checkup.

339
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:14,000
What have you got?

340
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:15,000
Nothing.

341
00:20:15,000 --> 00:20:17,000
I feed the fish

342
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:19,000
and take out the bloaters
for Martha.

343
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:21,000
She freaks out
if there's any bloaters.

344
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:22,000
There always are.

345
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:30,000
There we go. Good.

346
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:37,000
Heart sounds good.

347
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:39,000
Lungs, too.

348
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:41,000
Good.
Get out.

349
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:42,000
I have
sick people waiting.

350
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:45,000
Hear that? He's
kicking us out.

351
00:20:45,000 --> 00:20:46,000
We're too healthy.

352
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:48,000
I didn't say
you looked healthy.

353
00:20:48,000 --> 00:20:50,000
Don't even
start with me,
Uncle David.

354
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:52,000
We're having
a good day.

355
00:20:52,000 --> 00:20:54,000
Looks like
you need a break.

356
00:20:54,000 --> 00:20:55,000
You look tired.

357
00:20:55,000 --> 00:20:57,000
It's your
fluorescent
lighting.

358
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:00,000
Say "hasta la
bye-bye,
Uncle David."

359
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:01,000
Seriously, Dianne.

360
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:03,000
Seriously, stop.

361
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:05,000
Look, I moved in
with my mom.

362
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:07,000
She's retiring
just to be
with Julia.

363
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:08,000
We're fine.

364
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:12,000
( sighs )

365
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:15,000
Didn't mean
to bite your head off.

366
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:18,000
I have that effect on women.

367
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:22,000
Good-bye, sweetie.

368
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:23,000
Da...

369
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:25,000
Okay.

370
00:21:25,000 --> 00:21:26,000
Thank you.

371
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:27,000
All right?

372
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:28,000
Mm-hmm.

373
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:39,000
Okay, let's see
what we have here.

374
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:44,000
Oh, Julia, you won't believe
there's starfish in here.

375
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:46,000
Can I get you one?

376
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:48,000
Okay, I've got one.

377
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:51,000
Ooh, look at that.

378
00:21:51,000 --> 00:21:53,000
Gosh, look at that.

379
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:55,000
Look at the feet.

380
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:56,000
Kind of drippy.

381
00:21:56,000 --> 00:21:58,000
Cool.

382
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:22,000
All the little tentacles.

383
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:23,000
That's where
it sucks in...

384
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:25,000
Dianne!

385
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:29,000
Hey!

386
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:30,000
Starfish.

387
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:32,000
Okay.

388
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:37,000
Hey, you
want a ride?

389
00:22:37,000 --> 00:22:39,000
I can walk home.

390
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:41,000
Anybody who cleans
out that tank
deserves a ride.

391
00:22:41,000 --> 00:22:43,000
Come on.

392
00:22:43,000 --> 00:22:45,000
Got any plans
for the summer?

393
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:47,000
Mrs. Sobel says
I need a summer job.

394
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:49,000
I told her
I'd feed your fish

395
00:22:49,000 --> 00:22:50,000
but she said
that wasn't enough.

396
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:52,000
Who's Mrs. Sobel?

397
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:53,000
The case worker.

398
00:22:53,000 --> 00:22:54,000
I hate her.

399
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:57,000
Ever think about
being a mother's helper?

400
00:22:57,000 --> 00:22:58,000
You like kids?

401
00:22:58,000 --> 00:22:59,000
Well, that depends.

402
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:01,000
You can't just
"like kids."

403
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:02,000
They're all different.

404
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:05,000
No one ever says,
"So, do you like adults?"

405
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:06,000
Touche.

406
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:08,000
What does that mean?

407
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:10,000
It means you win.

408
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:12,000
You got me.
It's a fencing term.

409
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:13,000
It's French.

410
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:14,000
Well.

411
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:20,000
( train whistle blowing )

412
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:30,000
Is someone home?

413
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:32,000
My mom is.

414
00:23:32,000 --> 00:23:34,000
( rock music playing )

415
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:36,000
And boyfriend Bud.

416
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:37,000
Thanks for the ride.

417
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:38,000
Okay. See ya.

418
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:50,000
"Farewell, cow,
and farewell, cat

419
00:23:50,000 --> 00:23:54,000
"rabbit, tiger,
sullen rat.

420
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:55,000
"To our children
we shall say

421
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:57,000
"how we walked
the Milky Way.

422
00:23:57,000 --> 00:23:59,000
"You whose journeys
now begin

423
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:02,000
"if you reach
a lovely inn

424
00:24:02,000 --> 00:24:04,000
"if a rabbit
makes your bed

425
00:24:04,000 --> 00:24:07,000
"if two dragons
bake your bread

426
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:10,000
"rest a little
for my sake

427
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:12,000
and give my love
to William Blake."

428
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:16,000
That's a good
story, huh?

429
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:17,000
( door opens )

430
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:20,000
Did you ask David
to dinner?

431
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:21,000
Oh, I forgot.

432
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:22,000
Dianne.

433
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:24,000
What? I forgot.

434
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:25,000
I'll call him.

435
00:24:25,000 --> 00:24:27,000
No, Mom, please.

436
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:29,000
Do you want me to stop
having nightmares?

437
00:24:29,000 --> 00:24:30,000
David reminds me
of Mark.

438
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:31,000
Every time.

439
00:24:31,000 --> 00:24:32,000
Apples and oranges.

440
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:34,000
Something about
his voice... it's...

441
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:35,000
David's voice
is much deeper.

442
00:24:35,000 --> 00:24:37,000
It's exactly the same.

443
00:24:37,000 --> 00:24:39,000
All right, I will...

444
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:41,000
( sighs )

445
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:46,000
I could use a little help here.

446
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:58,000
( dog yelping and whining )

447
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:06,000
BUDDY:
Stop whining,
you worthless mutt!

448
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:09,000
( yelping and whining continue)
Come here!

449
00:25:09,000 --> 00:25:11,000
All right, that's it!
That's it!

450
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:13,000
Get in there!

451
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:18,000
You let him out.

452
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:20,000
What did I tell you, Amy?

453
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:23,000
I'm sorry.
I thought he needed exercise.

454
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:25,000
If you want a dog
to obey

455
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:27,000
first you got to break him.

456
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:28,000
Do you hear me?!

457
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:30,000
( whining
and yelping )

458
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:33,000
The whole neighborhood
can hear you.

459
00:25:33,000 --> 00:25:36,000
Hey, Amy Beth.

460
00:25:36,000 --> 00:25:38,000
Where'd you put
my cigarettes?

461
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:41,000
You told me not to buy you any,
remember?

462
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:42,000
You wanted to quit.

463
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:44,000
( laughs )

464
00:25:44,000 --> 00:25:46,000
I'll go.

465
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:48,000
We're out of hot sauce, anyway.

466
00:25:53,000 --> 00:25:55,000
Oh, cookie face

467
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:58,000
don't be gloomy.

468
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:01,000
Buddy's fun.

469
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:03,000
He doesn't like me.

470
00:26:03,000 --> 00:26:05,000
Don't be silly.

471
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:07,000
He loves you.

472
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:09,000
And don't be mad.

473
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:11,000
Go to bed... you got
school tomorrow.

474
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:12,000
School's out
for the summer.

475
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:15,000
It's over.

476
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:18,000
You had moving up ceremony?

477
00:26:19,000 --> 00:26:21,000
Oh, I wanted to come.

478
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:22,000
Why didn't you tell me?

479
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:24,000
I did.

480
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:25,000
No, you didn't.

481
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:28,000
You did? Did you?

482
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:36,000
It wasn't anything.

483
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:38,000
It was just a stupid assembly.

484
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:39,000
It doesn't matter.

485
00:26:40,000 --> 00:26:42,000
I'm not mad.

486
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:45,000
Oh... hug me.

487
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:48,000
Oh, I'm sorry.
I'm so sorry.

488
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:51,000
I'm so sorry.
I'm sorry.

489
00:27:07,000 --> 00:27:09,000
( electronic whirring )

490
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:23,000
( car horn honks )

491
00:27:26,000 --> 00:27:29,000
( car doors opening )

492
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:34,000
David.

493
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:35,000
Hey.

494
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:38,000
Hi.

495
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:42,000
Uh... Dianne,
this is Amy Williams.

496
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:43,000
I know Amy.

497
00:27:43,000 --> 00:27:45,000
You fish out the bloaters
for Martha, right?

498
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:48,000
Right.
Amy's looking
for a summer job.

499
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:51,000
Oh, that's great...
did you check the bulletin board

500
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:52,000
at the rec center?

501
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:55,000
Actually, I told her
you were looking for
a mother's helper.

502
00:27:56,000 --> 00:27:58,000
Oh.

503
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:00,000
Where's Julia?

504
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:03,000
She's sleeping.

505
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:04,000
Would you like some lemonade?

506
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:10,000
Let me give you a hand.

507
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:12,000
You can have
your lemonade

508
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:14,000
and then you can
get on your horse, cowboy.

509
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:16,000
I told you, I don't
need help with Julia.

510
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:17,000
Especially not
from a 12-year-old.

511
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:19,000
She's a good kid.

512
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:21,000
She's having some
trouble at home.

513
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:24,000
She remembered Julia.
She wanted to come.

514
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:28,000
Why? So she can tell
her friends at school?

515
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:30,000
I remember her, you know,
from the waiting room.

516
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:31,000
Well, Julia seems to like her.

517
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:34,000
She's awake.
They're having a little chat.

518
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:38,000
You like my watch?

519
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:40,000
It was my dad's.

520
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:41,000
It was being fixed
at the jewelers

521
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:43,000
the day his ship went down.

522
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:44,000
It glows in the dark, see?

523
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:46,000
Ma...

524
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:47,000
It's okay...
she's making lemonade.

525
00:28:47,000 --> 00:28:49,000
She'll be right back.

526
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:52,000
It's a guy's watch,
but I don't care.

527
00:28:52,000 --> 00:28:54,000
I've had it
six years now.

528
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:56,000
It's waterproof...
I even wear it in the shower.

529
00:28:56,000 --> 00:28:57,000
Hear it?

530
00:28:57,000 --> 00:28:59,000
JULIA:
Mee...

531
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:01,000
You want to wear it
while I'm here?

532
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:02,000
Oh, be careful.

533
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:05,000
It's too big... it might
fall off and break.

534
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:09,000
Oh... look at your
little wrists.

535
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:10,000
Your mom's right.

536
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:12,000
You can buy her
a kid's watch

537
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:15,000
at the drugstore
with different color straps.

538
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:16,000
Yeah, I've seen those.

539
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:17,000
Ba...

540
00:29:17,000 --> 00:29:18,000
They don't have blue.

541
00:29:18,000 --> 00:29:20,000
Yellow, red or green.

542
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:22,000
( whispering ):
Get yellow.

543
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:24,000
Can I push her chair out?

544
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:25,000
Okay.

545
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:31,000
Here comes the bump.

546
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:33,000
( both laughing )
Did you like that?

547
00:29:33,000 --> 00:29:35,000
Did your stomach
flip up?

548
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:37,000
Want to do it
again? Okay.

549
00:29:37,000 --> 00:29:41,000
Whoo! Was that fun?

550
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:43,000
She really likes that.

551
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:45,000
Yeah.

552
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:02,000
( seagulls crying )

553
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:12,000
Mee...

554
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:14,000
That's my name...

555
00:30:14,000 --> 00:30:16,000
don't wear it out.

556
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:19,000
Do you want to
trade hats? Here.

