828
00:47:44,000 --> 00:47:45,000
Look, I did it!

829
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:49,000
Thank you.

830
00:47:49,000 --> 00:47:50,000
Whoa!

831
00:48:02,000 --> 00:48:04,000
Dianne!

832
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:05,000
What? What? What?

833
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:06,000
What's wrong?

834
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:08,000
Okay, I got you.
I got you.

835
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:09,000
What's happening?

836
00:48:09,000 --> 00:48:10,000
Dianne, hold
down her tongue.

837
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:11,000
Get away. I know
what I'm doing.

838
00:48:11,000 --> 00:48:13,000
She's bleeding!

839
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:14,000
It's her lip.

840
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:16,000
Mom, call an ambulance.

841
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:18,000
I got you, sweetie.

842
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:19,000
Julia...

843
00:48:19,000 --> 00:48:20,000
I got you.

844
00:48:20,000 --> 00:48:21,000
It's okay.

845
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:22,000
It's all right.

846
00:48:22,000 --> 00:48:23,000
( phone rings )

847
00:48:23,000 --> 00:48:24,000
( answering machine clicks )

848
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:26,000
Hi. This is David McCune.

849
00:48:26,000 --> 00:48:29,000
I'm not here right now,
but you can leave a message.

850
00:48:29,000 --> 00:48:30,000
( beep )

851
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:32,000
David, it's Hannah.

852
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:35,000
We have a problem with Julia.

853
00:48:35,000 --> 00:48:37,000
Woman ( over PA):
Dr. Gelber. Dr. Gelber.

854
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:42,000
As soon as she's stable,
I want to transfer her to Mercy.

855
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:43,000
They don't know her here.

856
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:45,000
Hillcrest is
a good hospital.

857
00:48:45,000 --> 00:48:46,000
I know. It's just...

858
00:48:46,000 --> 00:48:49,000
I'm sure they're thinking,
"What's the point?"

859
00:48:49,000 --> 00:48:52,000
They're taking good
care of her, Dianne.

860
00:48:52,000 --> 00:48:54,000
The nurse asked me
if I want to speak

861
00:48:54,000 --> 00:48:56,000
to social services
about a hospice.

862
00:48:56,000 --> 00:48:59,000
I told her
Julia lives at home.

863
00:48:59,000 --> 00:49:02,000
Thank God, you've
never played me

864
00:49:02,000 --> 00:49:04,000
like a martyred mom
with a "special" kid.

865
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:08,000
David:
We'll see how she is
in the morning, okay?

866
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:09,000
Amy thinks
this was her fault.

867
00:49:09,000 --> 00:49:12,000
Can you please
tell her it wasn't?

868
00:49:12,000 --> 00:49:15,000
She took Julia
on the Ferris wheel.

869
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:18,000
The two of them?

870
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:20,000
Oh, if you'd seen her;

871
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:24,000
heard her when she got
to the top, she...

872
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:26,000
So excited.

873
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:29,000
My wild thing.

874
00:49:29,000 --> 00:49:32,000
You're not afraid,
are you?

875
00:49:32,000 --> 00:49:34,000
You'll try anything.

876
00:49:36,000 --> 00:49:40,000
Bet you could see everything
from up there.

877
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:49,000
DAVID:
I'll talk to Goodman.

878
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:53,000
He'll probably adjust her meds.

879
00:49:53,000 --> 00:49:56,000
And you just keep on going,
okay?

880
00:49:56,000 --> 00:49:58,000
Keep on loving her.

881
00:49:58,000 --> 00:50:00,000
Put it on there.

882
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:01,000
You got it?

883
00:50:04,000 --> 00:50:06,000
Good job.

884
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:08,000
Like that, Julia?

885
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:09,000
Good job.

886
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:10,000
AMY:
That's cool,
Julia.

887
00:50:10,000 --> 00:50:11,000
Good job.

888
00:50:16,000 --> 00:50:18,000
What do you think?

889
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:19,000
Uh.

890
00:50:19,000 --> 00:50:21,000
DIANNE:
No?

891
00:50:21,000 --> 00:50:24,000
( sighs )

892
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:27,000
You need something
for the Book Lovers Ball.

893
00:50:27,000 --> 00:50:29,000
Let's find you a dress.

894
00:50:29,000 --> 00:50:31,000
I don't need
to go to that.

895
00:50:31,000 --> 00:50:32,000
Yes, you do.

896
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:34,000
Hannah's the guest of honor.

897
00:50:34,000 --> 00:50:36,000
How about this? Come on.

898
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:37,000
Let's see.

899
00:50:37,000 --> 00:50:39,000
No, don't look at the tag.

900
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:40,000
It's a birthday present.

901
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:43,000
It's too much money
for a birthday present.

902
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:45,000
Besides, it's not
even my birthday.

903
00:50:45,000 --> 00:50:47,000
I got my first
dress-up dress here.

904
00:50:47,000 --> 00:50:48,000
( laughs )

905
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:49,000
I did, when my mother took me

906
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:52,000
to San Francisco
to see The Sound of Music.

907
00:50:52,000 --> 00:50:54,000
Every summer, we'd go,
we'd leave my dad at home

908
00:50:54,000 --> 00:50:57,000
and we'd go see a musical,
just the two of us.

909
00:50:57,000 --> 00:50:59,000
We'd stay in a hotel,
and we'd get room service

910
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:02,000
and we'd go to the evening
performance for grownups.

911
00:51:02,000 --> 00:51:04,000
I remember those
trips to the city.

912
00:51:04,000 --> 00:51:07,000
Your little overnight bag.

913
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:10,000
Now, there is a picture
of you somewhere

914
00:51:10,000 --> 00:51:14,000
in a red raincoat, standing
in front of the theater.

915
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:18,000
You should take Amy
to San Francisco

916
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:20,000
just for the night
to the theater.

917
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:22,000
Amy is not my daughter.

918
00:51:22,000 --> 00:51:25,000
Oh, here, sweetie,
let me...

919
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:27,000
No, Mom.

920
00:51:27,000 --> 00:51:29,000
One on each side.

921
00:51:29,000 --> 00:51:32,000
You don't want to look
like a little schoolgirl.

922
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:34,000
Just give it to me.

923
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:37,000
I like the way
Dianne does it.

924
00:51:42,000 --> 00:51:43,000
This way looks good, too.

925
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:45,000
Oh, wear it however you want.

926
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:46,000
I've got a headache.

927
00:51:46,000 --> 00:51:48,000
Buddy's going
to take you.

928
00:51:48,000 --> 00:51:50,000
( doorbell rings )

929
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:54,000
I asked Dianne to pick me up.

930
00:52:12,000 --> 00:52:15,000
Hi. How are you?

931
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:16,000
Hi. Good. Thank you.

932
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:18,000
I think it could
be lots of fun.

933
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:20,000
There's plenty
for them to do there.

934
00:52:20,000 --> 00:52:23,000
They could go
to the theater, museums.

935
00:52:23,000 --> 00:52:25,000
Why, it's just
for the weekend.

936
00:52:25,000 --> 00:52:27,000
Amy's never been
to San Francisco.

937
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:28,000
What about Julia?

938
00:52:28,000 --> 00:52:31,000
Oh, Julia
stays with me.

939
00:52:34,000 --> 00:52:36,000
HANNAH:
You know, Dianne's
never spent a night

940
00:52:36,000 --> 00:52:38,000
away from that child
in six years.

941
00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:40,000
It's not just Amy
I'm thinking about.

942
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:42,000
She won't do it.

943
00:52:42,000 --> 00:52:43,000
Well...

944
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:45,000
I'll talk to her.

945
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:47,000
Good.

946
00:52:47,000 --> 00:52:49,000
Mmm.

947
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:19,000
You lost?

948
00:53:19,000 --> 00:53:22,000
Um...

949
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:24,000
What are you
doing back here?

950
00:53:24,000 --> 00:53:26,000
Uh, just... inhaling.

951
00:53:26,000 --> 00:53:27,000
( inhales )

952
00:53:27,000 --> 00:53:28,000
I see.

953
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:31,000
I love the way
libraries smell.

954
00:53:31,000 --> 00:53:34,000
When I was little,
my mom used to bring me here

955
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:37,000
and I thought all the books
belonged to her.

956
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:39,000
My dad built these shelves.

957
00:53:39,000 --> 00:53:41,000
( sighs )

958
00:53:41,000 --> 00:53:44,000
I wish he could be here tonight.

959
00:53:47,000 --> 00:53:48,000
You look nice.

960
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:50,000
Thank you. You, too.

961
00:53:50,000 --> 00:53:51,000
Thanks.

962
00:53:51,000 --> 00:53:53,000
These are pretty.

963
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:56,000
Oh, they were
your grandmother's.

964
00:53:56,000 --> 00:53:57,000
Mark gave them to me.

965
00:53:57,000 --> 00:54:00,000
Ah, yes. That's why
they would seem familiar.

966
00:54:00,000 --> 00:54:03,000
( laughs )

967
00:54:03,000 --> 00:54:04,000
Let's dance.

968
00:54:06,000 --> 00:54:08,000
( giggling )

969
00:54:09,000 --> 00:54:11,000
BUDDY:
I cannot believe this!

970
00:54:11,000 --> 00:54:12,000
TESS:
I-I had to pay the rent...

971
00:54:12,000 --> 00:54:14,000
BUDDY:
No, no, no,
it's not okay.

972
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:16,000
You told me you
were going to
give me the money

973
00:54:16,000 --> 00:54:17,000
and now there's
no money.

974
00:54:17,000 --> 00:54:18,000
I-I'm not saying
it's okay.

975
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:21,000
I'm just saying I don't know
where to get the money from

976
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:22,000
because it's already
gone out, that's all.

977
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:24,000
It's already
gone out.

978
00:54:24,000 --> 00:54:26,000
You told me I was
going to be able
to get this amp.

979
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:27,000
I have a gig
tomorrow night!

980
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:29,000
We'll try and figure it out
as soon as I get the next...

981
00:54:29,000 --> 00:54:30,000
"Try and figure..."?

982
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:31,000
What do you
want me to do?

983
00:54:31,000 --> 00:54:32,000
What do you want me
to say?

984
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:34,000
I want you to give
me the money

985
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:36,000
that you told me you
were going to give me!

986
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:38,000
Okay, okay, okay!

987
00:54:38,000 --> 00:54:39,000
Just shut up
and stop this!

988
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:40,000
( slapping )

989
00:54:40,000 --> 00:54:41,000
( Tess screams and gasps )

990
00:54:41,000 --> 00:54:43,000
I'm outta here!

991
00:54:43,000 --> 00:54:45,000
( Tess sobs )

992
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:47,000
( door slams )

993
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:50,000
( sobbing continues )

994
00:54:50,000 --> 00:54:52,000
( van drives away )

995
00:54:52,000 --> 00:54:55,000
( dog yelping and whining )

996
00:55:00,000 --> 00:55:02,000
Knock it off!

997
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:04,000
( dog quiets )

998
00:55:06,000 --> 00:55:08,000
Where's your mother?

999
00:55:08,000 --> 00:55:10,000
She's sleeping.

1000
00:55:10,000 --> 00:55:13,000
She said she's
tired and she just
wants to sleep.

1001
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:15,000
Did you have
breakfast?

1002
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:17,000
Get out of my way.

1003
00:55:17,000 --> 00:55:20,000
No.

1004
00:55:23,000 --> 00:55:24,000
( dog yelping )

1005
00:55:24,000 --> 00:55:26,000
Shut up!

1006
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:28,000
I said shut up!

1007
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:30,000
Buddy...

1008
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:32,000
Go get me
one of your pillowcases.

1009
00:55:32,000 --> 00:55:34,000
Buddy, you can't.
You can't.

1010
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:36,000
He's just a puppy.
He can still learn.

1011
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:39,000
I swear I'll never
touch him again.

1012
00:55:39,000 --> 00:55:40,000
Go get me
a pillowcase!

1013
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:42,000
No.

1014
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:02,000
Amy!

1015
00:56:18,000 --> 00:56:20,000
( horn honking )

1016
00:56:24,000 --> 00:56:26,000
( horn honks )

1017
00:56:26,000 --> 00:56:28,000
( brakes squeal )

1018
00:56:35,000 --> 00:56:37,000
No... no... no...

1019
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:39,000
Ow! Ow!

1020
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:40,000
( sobbing )

1021
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:44,000
Get in there!

1022
00:56:44,000 --> 00:56:46,000
( sobbing )

1023
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:48,000
( whimpering )

1024
00:56:48,000 --> 00:56:50,000
Now, you leave him
in there.

1025
00:56:50,000 --> 00:56:52,000
( sobbing )

1026
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:25,000
Okay, get out.

1027
00:57:25,000 --> 00:57:27,000
You can walk from here.

1028
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:29,000
Say "Thank you, Buddy."

1029
00:57:29,000 --> 00:57:31,000
Thank you, Buddy.

1030
00:57:31,000 --> 00:57:32,000
Oh, no, no,
no, no, no.

1031
00:57:32,000 --> 00:57:33,000
I said you can walk.

1032
00:57:33,000 --> 00:57:35,000
He's going for
a little swim.

1033
00:57:35,000 --> 00:57:36,000
No!
Hey!

1034
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:38,000
Ow...

1035
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:43,000
( yelping )

1036
00:57:43,000 --> 00:57:45,000
( yelping louder )

1037
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:50,000
No... no... no...!

1038
00:57:50,000 --> 00:57:53,000
Buddy, Buddy, no!

1039
00:57:53,000 --> 00:57:55,000
Buddy, please...

1040
00:57:55,000 --> 00:57:56,000
Get off of me.

1041
00:57:56,000 --> 00:57:57,000
Please don't!

1042
00:57:57,000 --> 00:58:00,000
Get out of here.

1043
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:02,000
Buddy...

1044
00:58:02,000 --> 00:58:06,000
I told you, a dog
who won't train
isn't worth jack.

1045
00:58:06,000 --> 00:58:07,000
No!

1046
00:58:07,000 --> 00:58:08,000
( yelping )

1047
00:58:08,000 --> 00:58:10,000
No!

1048
00:58:28,000 --> 00:58:30,000
Amy Williams.
I'm her mother.

1049
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:32,000
Where is she?
I'm her mother.

1050
00:58:32,000 --> 00:58:34,000
Was she admitted
in the last hour?

1051
00:58:34,000 --> 00:58:35,000
Yes. They said she was here.

1052
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:37,000
Amy... Williams.

1053
00:58:37,000 --> 00:58:38,000
She's fine.

1054
00:58:38,000 --> 00:58:39,000
Are you sure?

1055
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:40,000
I just saw her.

1056
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:41,000
She made it to
shore with the dog.

1057
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:44,000
( relieved gasps )

1058
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:46,000
Where is she?
I want to see her.

1059
00:58:46,000 --> 00:58:47,000
You got a cigarette?

1060
00:58:47,000 --> 00:58:48,000
Tess, listen...
they arrested Buddy.

1061
00:58:48,000 --> 00:58:50,000
What?

1062
00:58:50,000 --> 00:58:52,000
Come here.
Come here.

1063
00:58:52,000 --> 00:58:56,000
You have got to get
into a treatment
center... now.

1064
00:58:56,000 --> 00:58:58,000
This is it, Tess.
Child Services

1065
00:58:58,000 --> 00:59:00,000
has issued an order of
protection against you.

1066
00:59:00,000 --> 00:59:01,000
Mommy?

1067
00:59:01,000 --> 00:59:03,000
Wha...? Baby...

1068
00:59:03,000 --> 00:59:05,000
Oh, honey.

1069
00:59:05,000 --> 00:59:06,000
Oh... oh...

1070
00:59:25,000 --> 00:59:27,000
Say good night
to Julia.

1071
00:59:27,000 --> 00:59:30,000
And don't
wake her up.

1072
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:33,000
You got to keep it
nice and quiet.

1073
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:35,000
Amy...

1074
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:38,000
Do you want some hot chocolate?

1075
00:59:39,000 --> 00:59:41,000
Come on.

1076
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:49,000
When I was a kid,
I used to sleep out
here in the summer.

1077
00:59:49,000 --> 00:59:52,000
I'd lie on my back and
try to count the stars.

1078
00:59:52,000 --> 00:59:54,000
You can't;
there's too many.

1079
00:59:56,000 --> 00:59:58,000
Do you believe
in Heaven, Dianne?

1080
00:59:58,000 --> 00:59:59,000
Absolutely.

1081
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:02,000
I think my dad can see me
from Heaven.

1082
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:05,000
And I know he helped me
get to shore today.

1083
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:07,000
I know he did.

1084
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:11,000
I wish he could come back.

1085
01:00:11,000 --> 01:00:12,000
So do I.

1086
01:00:12,000 --> 01:00:16,000
Julia misses her dad.

1087
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:18,000
She's never met him.

1088
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:19,000
His boat could sink.

1089
01:00:19,000 --> 01:00:22,000
He could drown,
just like my dad

1090
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:23,000
then it would be too late.

1091
01:00:23,000 --> 01:00:25,000
Oh...

1092
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:27,000
( sniffling )

1093
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:30,000
Hey, it's clearing. Look.

1094
01:00:35,000 --> 01:00:37,000
( gasps )

1095
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:39,000
Did you see that?

1096
01:00:39,000 --> 01:00:40,000
Yeah. Did you make a wish?

1097
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:41,000
Yeah. Did you?

1098
01:00:41,000 --> 01:00:43,000
Yeah.

1099
01:00:57,000 --> 01:00:59,000
( weary sigh )

1100
01:01:04,000 --> 01:01:06,000
TESS:
You want to take her
to San Francisco?

1101
01:01:06,000 --> 01:01:08,000
Yeah. To see a play.

1102
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:11,000
I said she couldn't go
without your permission.

1103
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:15,000
Taking her places,
buying her clothes...

1104
01:01:15,000 --> 01:01:17,000
I'm grateful to you.

1105
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:19,000
You don't need to be.

1106
01:01:19,000 --> 01:01:20,000
I like Amy very much.

1107
01:01:20,000 --> 01:01:22,000
She thinks you
hung the moon.

1108
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:24,000
( chuckles )

1109
01:01:26,000 --> 01:01:29,000
You're going
to be okay, Tess.

1110
01:01:30,000 --> 01:01:33,000
After Ryan died,
I... couldn't sleep.

1111
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:35,000
Pills didn't work.

1112
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:38,000
I drink so I can
sleep, that's all.

1113
01:01:40,000 --> 01:01:43,000
I'm not very good
at being alone.

1114
01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:44,000
Mom!

1115
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:50,000
Hi.

1116
01:01:52,000 --> 01:01:55,000
When you're better, I
can come home, right?

1117
01:01:55,000 --> 01:01:58,000
I'm your mother.
We belong together.

1118
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:01,000
AMY:
Love you.

1119
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:04,000
( horn blaring )

1120
01:02:04,000 --> 01:02:06,000
Amy!

1121
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:16,000
( monitor beeping )

1122
01:02:23,000 --> 01:02:25,000
Dianne?

1123
01:02:25,000 --> 01:02:28,000
Dianne.

1124
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:30,000
Dianne.

1125
01:02:42,000 --> 01:02:44,000
Would you like to
see your daughter?

1126
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:53,000
Not now.

1127
01:03:19,000 --> 01:03:21,000
( pager beeping )

1128
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:23,000
( groaning )

1129
01:03:36,000 --> 01:03:38,000
( monitor beeping )

1130
01:04:02,000 --> 01:04:04,000
Dianne.

1131
01:04:23,000 --> 01:04:25,000
NURSE ( on P.A. ):
Code Blue, E.R. Two.

1132
01:04:25,000 --> 01:04:27,000
Code Blue, E.R. Two.

1133
01:04:27,000 --> 01:04:29,000
Code Blue, E.R. Two.

1134
01:04:32,000 --> 01:04:35,000
( woman screaming )

1135
01:04:37,000 --> 01:04:40,000
( yelling )

1136
01:04:40,000 --> 01:04:42,000
( alarm beeping )

1137
01:04:44,000 --> 01:04:46,000
DOCTOR:
Losing her!
Losing her!

1138
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:16,000
( monitor beeps steadily )

1139
01:05:16,000 --> 01:05:18,000
( respirator pumping )

1140
01:05:56,000 --> 01:05:58,000
Done with that?

1141
01:06:03,000 --> 01:06:05,000
Thanks for
the call.

1142
01:06:10,000 --> 01:06:12,000
Seems like old times.

1143
01:06:12,000 --> 01:06:13,000
Not really.

1144
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:15,000
I meant when Mom
was in the hospital.

1145
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:18,000
I know what
you meant.

1146
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:20,000
What are you
doing here, Mark?

1147
01:06:20,000 --> 01:06:23,000
The hospital
got in touch with me.

1148
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:27,000
Well... you don't
need to stick around.

1149
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:29,000
Dianne's not your
responsibility.

1150
01:06:32,000 --> 01:06:33,000
Order something else.
I'm buying.

1151
01:06:33,000 --> 01:06:35,000
Just coffee.

1152
01:06:42,000 --> 01:06:45,000
I thought you'd
be married by now,
have a couple of kids.

1153
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:48,000
Seeing anyone?

1154
01:06:48,000 --> 01:06:51,000
20 patients a day,
on the average.

1155
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:53,000
Here's one of them.

1156
01:07:01,000 --> 01:07:02,000
She's my niece.

1157
01:07:02,000 --> 01:07:04,000
It's recent.

1158
01:07:04,000 --> 01:07:06,000
Taken about
a month ago.

1159
01:07:06,000 --> 01:07:08,000
Keep it.

1160
01:07:10,000 --> 01:07:12,000
She's your daughter...

1161
01:07:12,000 --> 01:07:14,000
doesn't that mean
anything to you?

1162
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:15,000
I send a check
every month.

1163
01:07:15,000 --> 01:07:17,000
It's not like
I'm a deadbeat dad.

1164
01:07:17,000 --> 01:07:19,000
Now what?

1165
01:07:19,000 --> 01:07:21,000
You going to pay
for her funeral?

1166
01:07:26,000 --> 01:07:28,000
Yeah. A few months,
at the most.

1167
01:07:30,000 --> 01:07:32,000
Makes me sick,
all of it.

1168
01:07:32,000 --> 01:07:34,000
Six years wasted.

1169
01:07:37,000 --> 01:07:40,000
You know, Dianne takes her
to the beach sometimes.

1170
01:07:40,000 --> 01:07:42,000
They sing together.

1171
01:07:42,000 --> 01:07:45,000
Julia laughs when
you tickle her.

1172
01:07:45,000 --> 01:07:48,000
She's got a great laugh.

1173
01:07:48,000 --> 01:07:50,000
You missed out, brother.

1174
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:54,000
You can call it a waste, if that
makes you feel better about it.

1175
01:07:54,000 --> 01:07:57,000
Put that back
in your wallet, huh?

1176
01:07:57,000 --> 01:08:00,000
You tell everyone
that Dianne's your wife,
or is it a private game?

1177
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:06,000
Whoa! Hey!
Knock it off!

1178
01:08:11,000 --> 01:08:13,000
Sorry.

1179
01:08:31,000 --> 01:08:32,000
Dr. McCune?

1180
01:08:32,000 --> 01:08:33,000
What is it?

1181
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:35,000
Dianne Parker's awake.

1182
01:08:35,000 --> 01:08:36,000
She's asking for you.

1183
01:08:36,000 --> 01:08:37,000
Great.

1184
01:08:49,000 --> 01:08:51,000
Where's David?

1185
01:08:52,000 --> 01:08:53,000
What?

1186
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:56,000
Where is David?

1187
01:08:56,000 --> 01:08:59,000
He's not here yet.

1188
01:08:59,000 --> 01:09:00,000
Amy?

1189
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:02,000
She's okay.

1190
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:04,000
I'm not lying to you.

1191
01:09:04,000 --> 01:09:06,000
You want me to
get the nurse?

1192
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:08,000
You're here.

1193
01:09:08,000 --> 01:09:12,000
Yeah. You had my business card
in your bag.

1194
01:09:12,000 --> 01:09:16,000
I'm sorry.

1195
01:09:16,000 --> 01:09:17,000
You can go.

1196
01:09:17,000 --> 01:09:19,000
What? You kidding?

1197
01:09:19,000 --> 01:09:22,000
You hate hospitals.

1198
01:09:24,000 --> 01:09:26,000
I'm not going
to lose you again.

1199
01:09:26,000 --> 01:09:30,000
Am I dying?

1200
01:09:30,000 --> 01:09:31,000
No.

1201
01:09:33,000 --> 01:09:34,000
Not on my watch.

1202
01:09:55,000 --> 01:09:58,000
TESS:
My little girl was hit by a car.

1203
01:09:58,000 --> 01:09:59,000
She's okay.

1204
01:10:01,000 --> 01:10:02,000
A drunk driver.

1205
01:10:06,000 --> 01:10:09,000
You say trust in
your higher power.

1206
01:10:09,000 --> 01:10:10,000
Why should I
trust something

1207
01:10:10,000 --> 01:10:13,000
that sends a storm
to drown Ryan

1208
01:10:13,000 --> 01:10:15,000
or a car to hit
my little girl?

1209
01:10:16,000 --> 01:10:18,000
If God wants to
teach me a lesson

1210
01:10:18,000 --> 01:10:21,000
why doesn't he send a
drunk driver to hit me?

1211
01:10:21,000 --> 01:10:23,000
I mean, that's fair

1212
01:10:23,000 --> 01:10:26,000
but Amy's just
a little girl.

1213
01:10:26,000 --> 01:10:29,000
She's never, ever
done anything bad.

1214
01:10:33,000 --> 01:10:37,000
If there is some master plan,
I don't see it.

1215
01:10:37,000 --> 01:10:40,000
I'd like to, 'cause
whatever it is

1216
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:44,000
it's got to be better
than what I've been doing.

1217
01:10:46,000 --> 01:10:49,000
AMY:
I'm not going back.

1218
01:10:49,000 --> 01:10:50,000
Not until you do.

1219
01:10:50,000 --> 01:10:52,000
You can tell Julia
I'm all right.

1220
01:10:52,000 --> 01:10:55,000
I don't want her to be scared.

1221
01:10:55,000 --> 01:10:56,000
Hannah's there.

1222
01:10:56,000 --> 01:10:59,000
You understand her
better than anybody.

1223
01:10:59,000 --> 01:11:01,000
She trusts you.

1224
01:11:01,000 --> 01:11:03,000
I can't leave
until you're okay.

1225
01:11:03,000 --> 01:11:05,000
( sobbing )

1226
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:08,000
Amy.

1227
01:11:08,000 --> 01:11:09,000
It's my fault.

1228
01:11:09,000 --> 01:11:12,000
We came here
because of me.

1229
01:11:12,000 --> 01:11:14,000
Everybody gets hurt
because of me.

1230
01:11:14,000 --> 01:11:16,000
I don't take good
care of Julia.

1231
01:11:16,000 --> 01:11:18,000
Look what happened
at the carnival.

1232
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:21,000
I didn't take good care
of my mom, either.

1233
01:11:21,000 --> 01:11:22,000
I hurt people.

1234
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:24,000
I hurt everybody.

1235
01:11:24,000 --> 01:11:26,000
Oh, Amy, no.

1236
01:11:26,000 --> 01:11:27,000
It's okay.

1237
01:11:28,000 --> 01:11:29,000
Listen...

1238
01:11:29,000 --> 01:11:32,000
sometimes I feel
just the way you said.

1239
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:34,000
'Cause I can't
fix something,
it's my fault.

1240
01:11:34,000 --> 01:11:36,000
I'm a doctor... I'm supposed
to make everything okay.

1241
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:38,000
But I can't.

1242
01:11:38,000 --> 01:11:40,000
We can't, Amy.

1243
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:45,000
We can't stop...

1244
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:48,000
taxis from jumping the curb
or boats from sinking.

1245
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:50,000
We just do
what we can

1246
01:11:50,000 --> 01:11:52,000
and try not
to blame ourselves

1247
01:11:52,000 --> 01:11:53,000
or anybody else,
that's it.

1248
01:11:53,000 --> 01:11:56,000
I made Julia have a
seizure at the carnival.

1249
01:11:56,000 --> 01:11:57,000
Julia's had seizures before

1250
01:11:57,000 --> 01:11:59,000
It isn't anything you did.

1251
01:11:59,000 --> 01:12:01,000
This has been the best summer

1252
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:04,000
of her life, Amy.

1253
01:12:04,000 --> 01:12:05,000
Come here.

1254
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:11,000
Do you know what
it's meant to me

1255
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:13,000
for Julia to have a friend?

1256
01:12:15,000 --> 01:12:17,000
I don't think
I can tell you.

1257
01:12:17,000 --> 01:12:21,000
Not in words.

1258
01:12:21,000 --> 01:12:25,000
Your mother wants
to get better because of you.

1259
01:12:25,000 --> 01:12:29,000
Don't you see, it's just
the opposite of what you think.

1260
01:12:29,000 --> 01:12:31,000
You're so good...

1261
01:12:31,000 --> 01:12:34,000
for everyone.

1262
01:12:35,000 --> 01:12:37,000
Can you do something for me?

1263
01:12:37,000 --> 01:12:40,000
It's important.

1264
01:12:40,000 --> 01:12:42,000
Go back.

1265
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:44,000
Tell Julia I love her

1266
01:12:44,000 --> 01:12:47,000
and I'm coming home.

1267
01:12:47,000 --> 01:12:49,000
Okay?

1268
01:12:49,000 --> 01:12:52,000
Thank you.

1269
01:13:18,000 --> 01:13:19,000
I went to three
different places.

1270
01:13:19,000 --> 01:13:22,000
No one had lilacs.

1271
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:35,000
I guess this isn't
a good time to talk.

1272
01:13:35,000 --> 01:13:37,000
There's nothing
to talk about.

1273
01:13:39,000 --> 01:13:42,000
You still had my
card in your handbag.

1274
01:13:42,000 --> 01:13:44,000
I gave that to you
when we went dancing

1275
01:13:44,000 --> 01:13:46,000
on the pier
six years ago.

1276
01:13:48,000 --> 01:13:50,000
It's an evening bag.

1277
01:13:50,000 --> 01:13:51,000
I never use it.

1278
01:13:51,000 --> 01:13:54,000
Don't turn this into something.

1279
01:13:54,000 --> 01:13:57,000
You know, I was docking
when the hospital called.

1280
01:13:57,000 --> 01:14:00,000
Docking here in San Francisco,
a cab ride away.

1281
01:14:00,000 --> 01:14:02,000
What are the odds on that?

1282
01:14:02,000 --> 01:14:03,000
I'm tired.

1283
01:14:03,000 --> 01:14:06,000
We're meant to
be together.

1284
01:14:06,000 --> 01:14:09,000
We're getting
a second chance.

1285
01:14:12,000 --> 01:14:14,000
Dianne...

1286
01:14:17,000 --> 01:14:20,000
I'm not going
to leave this time.

1287
01:14:27,000 --> 01:14:29,000
All right?

1288
01:14:29,000 --> 01:14:30,000
I appreciate it.

1289
01:14:30,000 --> 01:14:31,000
Thanks.

1290
01:14:31,000 --> 01:14:33,000
Okay. I've arranged
for an ambulance

1291
01:14:33,000 --> 01:14:36,000
to take Dianne to the
hospital in Hawthorne

1292
01:14:36,000 --> 01:14:37,000
as soon as she's
ready to be moved.

1293
01:14:37,000 --> 01:14:39,000
She can have the
knee surgery there

1294
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:40,000
maybe by Friday.

1295
01:14:40,000 --> 01:14:41,000
I'll stay here with her.

1296
01:14:41,000 --> 01:14:42,000
You can go back.

1297
01:14:42,000 --> 01:14:44,000
Uh...

1298
01:14:44,000 --> 01:14:47,000
Look, I never stopped
thinking about her

1299
01:14:47,000 --> 01:14:48,000
not one day.

1300
01:14:48,000 --> 01:14:51,000
Things could
have been different.

1301
01:14:51,000 --> 01:14:52,000
Now they are.

1302
01:14:52,000 --> 01:14:53,000
Dianne wants you to stay?

1303
01:14:53,000 --> 01:14:55,000
Ask her.

1304
01:15:16,000 --> 01:15:18,000
TESS:
I've had enough therapy.

1305
01:15:18,000 --> 01:15:20,000
I want to go home.

1306
01:15:20,000 --> 01:15:21,000
Amy's coming back.

1307
01:15:21,000 --> 01:15:23,000
She's got her arm
in a cast.

1308
01:15:23,000 --> 01:15:26,000
She's going to need help
getting dressed.

1309
01:15:26,000 --> 01:15:27,000
You're not ready.

1310
01:15:27,000 --> 01:15:29,000
You need more time, Tess.

1311
01:15:29,000 --> 01:15:31,000
I want it to be me.

1312
01:15:31,000 --> 01:15:34,000
I want to be the one
to help her, not somebody else.

1313
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:35,000
The important thing now

1314
01:15:35,000 --> 01:15:38,000
is to help yourself
and to get better.

1315
01:15:38,000 --> 01:15:40,000
Helping Amy would
help me get better.

1316
01:15:40,000 --> 01:15:44,000
I want to think
about somebody else.

1317
01:15:44,000 --> 01:15:46,000
When I think
about myself

1318
01:15:46,000 --> 01:15:48,000
I don't want
to get better.

1319
01:15:48,000 --> 01:15:52,000
I don't get how people
can forgive themselves.

1320
01:15:52,000 --> 01:15:54,000
I don't understand how
to say life is not so bad

1321
01:15:54,000 --> 01:15:55,000
when it is.

1322
01:15:55,000 --> 01:15:57,000
You're going to feel
pain sometimes, Tess

1323
01:15:57,000 --> 01:15:59,000
but you can handle that.

1324
01:15:59,000 --> 01:16:00,000
No one's happy all the time.

1325
01:16:00,000 --> 01:16:03,000
It's what you do with it.

1326
01:16:07,000 --> 01:16:08,000
I want to go home.

1327
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:12,000
I'll feel better
once I know you're there.

1328
01:16:12,000 --> 01:16:13,000
I'll leave tonight,
if you want.

1329
01:16:14,000 --> 01:16:16,000
Mark says he'll
stay around

1330
01:16:16,000 --> 01:16:18,000
until they
transfer you.

1331
01:16:18,000 --> 01:16:20,000
Unless you don't
want him here.

1332
01:16:20,000 --> 01:16:23,000
I can have Greenwald
restrict your visitors.

1333
01:16:23,000 --> 01:16:25,000
No.

1334
01:16:25,000 --> 01:16:28,000
I need to forgive him.

1335
01:16:28,000 --> 01:16:31,000
For my sake as much
as for Julia's.

1336
01:16:33,000 --> 01:16:34,000
You still love him?

1337
01:16:36,000 --> 01:16:37,000
I'm sorry.

1338
01:16:39,000 --> 01:16:40,000
None of my business.

1339
01:16:44,000 --> 01:16:46,000
I need time.

1340
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:49,000
That's all I can think about
right now is time.

1341
01:16:49,000 --> 01:16:53,000
Julia has so little left.

1342
01:16:56,000 --> 01:16:57,000
He doesn't know that.

1343
01:16:57,000 --> 01:16:58,000
I haven't told him.

1344
01:17:00,000 --> 01:17:01,000
I don't know, David.

1345
01:17:01,000 --> 01:17:03,000
It's hard to think right now.

1346
01:17:05,000 --> 01:17:07,000
He never took off
his wedding band.

1347
01:18:19,000 --> 01:18:20,000
Here, baby, just...
just take it.

1348
01:18:20,000 --> 01:18:22,000
I'll see you at
Hawthorne, okay?

1349
01:18:22,000 --> 01:18:23,000
Bye.

1350
01:18:23,000 --> 01:18:24,000
Bye.

1351
01:19:05,000 --> 01:19:07,000
There she is!
Julia!

1352
01:19:07,000 --> 01:19:11,000
Hi! Hi, sweetie.

1353
01:19:11,000 --> 01:19:12,000
Oh...

1354
01:19:15,000 --> 01:19:16,000
How's my girl?

1355
01:19:16,000 --> 01:19:17,000
How's my girl?

1356
01:19:17,000 --> 01:19:18,000
You look good.

1357
01:19:18,000 --> 01:19:20,000
I missed you so much.

1358
01:19:20,000 --> 01:19:22,000
How's Amy?

1359
01:19:22,000 --> 01:19:23,000
She's doing fine.

1360
01:19:23,000 --> 01:19:25,000
David's watching her.

1361
01:19:25,000 --> 01:19:27,000
Here, give me that.

1362
01:19:35,000 --> 01:19:37,000
Do I tell you I'd
be lost without you

1363
01:19:37,000 --> 01:19:38,000
or do you know it?

1364
01:19:38,000 --> 01:19:40,000
I think you'd manage.

1365
01:19:40,000 --> 01:19:44,000
Dianne, I have a lot
of respect for you...

1366
01:19:44,000 --> 01:19:45,000
as a person,
as a woman.

1367
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:48,000
And not just because
you're my daughter.

1368
01:19:55,000 --> 01:19:56,000
Mom...

1369
01:19:58,000 --> 01:20:00,000
Mark was in
San Francisco.

1370
01:20:00,000 --> 01:20:03,000
I know.
David told me.

1371
01:20:03,000 --> 01:20:06,000
He wants to come back.

1372
01:20:06,000 --> 01:20:10,000
He wants to get
married again.

1373
01:20:10,000 --> 01:20:11,000
Well, whatever
you decide

1374
01:20:11,000 --> 01:20:13,000
you'll be doing
the right thing.

1375
01:20:13,000 --> 01:20:15,000
I want to know
what you think.

1376
01:20:15,000 --> 01:20:18,000
That you deserve
to be happy

1377
01:20:18,000 --> 01:20:21,000
and no one can
define that for you.

1378
01:20:21,000 --> 01:20:24,000
I never really forgave him.

1379
01:20:24,000 --> 01:20:26,000
I can now.

1380
01:20:26,000 --> 01:20:28,000
He's changed now.

1381
01:20:28,000 --> 01:20:31,000
He's... he's older.

1382
01:20:31,000 --> 01:20:33,000
I'm older, too.

1383
01:20:35,000 --> 01:20:36,000
I'm not expecting it to be

1384
01:20:36,000 --> 01:20:38,000
exactly the way it
was, you know.

1385
01:20:38,000 --> 01:20:40,000
I mean, a lot's happened
in six years.

1386
01:20:40,000 --> 01:20:43,000
To you it has.

1387
01:20:45,000 --> 01:20:47,000
I wish I were certain.

1388
01:20:47,000 --> 01:20:51,000
I was so certain
when we got married.

1389
01:20:51,000 --> 01:20:53,000
Mark's sure.

1390
01:20:53,000 --> 01:20:55,000
He says we're meant
to be together.

1391
01:20:55,000 --> 01:20:57,000
Mmm.

1392
01:20:57,000 --> 01:20:58,000
Is that his wedding ring?

1393
01:20:58,000 --> 01:21:01,000
He never stopped wearing it.

1394
01:21:01,000 --> 01:21:02,000
He made me take it.

1395
01:21:02,000 --> 01:21:06,000
No one's ever made you
do anything.

1396
01:21:17,000 --> 01:21:20,000
It's not too late for Julia
to know her father...

1397
01:21:20,000 --> 01:21:22,000
that's what I keep thinking.

1398
01:21:44,000 --> 01:21:45,000
( knocking )

1399
01:21:45,000 --> 01:21:47,000
Who do you have to know

1400
01:21:47,000 --> 01:21:48,000
to get a shave
around here?

1401
01:21:48,000 --> 01:21:50,000
Come on in.

1402
01:21:58,000 --> 01:22:00,000
Hey.
Hi.

1403
01:22:00,000 --> 01:22:02,000
I'll leave the key for you
on the kitchen table.

1404
01:22:02,000 --> 01:22:03,000
Thanks.

1405
01:22:03,000 --> 01:22:04,000
It's your house, too.

1406
01:22:04,000 --> 01:22:07,000
Yeah, I don't see
bunking at her mother's.

1407
01:22:07,000 --> 01:22:11,000
Put a good word in for me
with Hannah, I'd appreciate it.

1408
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:13,000
How's Dianne?

1409
01:22:13,000 --> 01:22:15,000
Been to see her?

1410
01:22:15,000 --> 01:22:17,000
She's got enough visitors
without me hanging around.

1411
01:22:17,000 --> 01:22:19,000
If you hurry up, I'll
take you to the hospital.

1412
01:22:19,000 --> 01:22:21,000
Uh, I'll get a cab.

1413
01:22:21,000 --> 01:22:23,000
Wish me luck.

1414
01:22:23,000 --> 01:22:25,000
Good luck.

1415
01:22:25,000 --> 01:22:27,000
Hey, you know,
I've been thinking

1416
01:22:27,000 --> 01:22:29,000
Dianne and I should
move up to Portland.

1417
01:22:29,000 --> 01:22:31,000
Get a really fresh start.

1418
01:22:31,000 --> 01:22:33,000
I got enough money
to put down on a place...

1419
01:22:33,000 --> 01:22:35,000
nothing grand.

1420
01:22:35,000 --> 01:22:36,000
You know Seaside?

1421
01:22:36,000 --> 01:22:38,000
Just north of Rockaway Beach.

1422
01:22:38,000 --> 01:22:40,000
I brought some pictures.

1423
01:22:50,000 --> 01:22:52,000
Oh, it looks like
you got company.

1424
01:22:52,000 --> 01:22:53,000
Hey.

1425
01:22:53,000 --> 01:22:54,000
You want to stay in
the chair for a while?

1426
01:22:54,000 --> 01:22:55,000
Yeah, thanks.

1427
01:22:55,000 --> 01:22:57,000
All right, no dancing.

1428
01:22:57,000 --> 01:22:59,000
You weren't here.
I thought I got stood up.

1429
01:22:59,000 --> 01:23:01,000
I was in X ray.
I'm sorry.

1430
01:23:01,000 --> 01:23:03,000
Someone should
have told you.

1431
01:23:03,000 --> 01:23:04,000
Nah, I didn't ask.

1432
01:23:04,000 --> 01:23:05,000
Hey, look,
let's get out of here.

1433
01:23:05,000 --> 01:23:07,000
I can't propose
sitting next to a bedpan.

1434
01:23:07,000 --> 01:23:09,000
Mark, uh...

1435
01:23:09,000 --> 01:23:11,000
Yes, I can.

1436
01:23:11,000 --> 01:23:13,000
( sighs )

1437
01:23:13,000 --> 01:23:14,000
Marry me.

1438
01:23:14,000 --> 01:23:15,000
Please.

1439
01:23:15,000 --> 01:23:16,000
Are you sure?

1440
01:23:16,000 --> 01:23:18,000
Yes. I love you.

1441
01:23:18,000 --> 01:23:20,000
I never stopped missing you.

1442
01:23:20,000 --> 01:23:23,000
You know, I hate that we lost
these six years

1443
01:23:23,000 --> 01:23:24,000
and I want to make
them up somehow.

1444
01:23:24,000 --> 01:23:26,000
I don't think they were lost...
I lived them.

1445
01:23:26,000 --> 01:23:29,000
You're right, you're right.

1446
01:23:29,000 --> 01:23:33,000
It's not starting over,
it's starting now.

1447
01:23:33,000 --> 01:23:35,000
Everything's a first, okay?

1448
01:23:35,000 --> 01:23:38,000
'Kay.

1449
01:23:38,000 --> 01:23:40,000
I knew right
when I saw it.

1450
01:23:40,000 --> 01:23:43,000
Isn't that a great
old farm house?

1451
01:23:43,000 --> 01:23:44,000
Yeah.

1452
01:23:44,000 --> 01:23:46,000
Just an hour
north of Portland.

1453
01:23:46,000 --> 01:23:49,000
It's great, but we can't
take Julie to a farmhouse

1454
01:23:49,000 --> 01:23:50,000
in the middle of nowhere.

1455
01:23:50,000 --> 01:23:52,000
All her doctors are here.

1456
01:23:52,000 --> 01:23:54,000
I meant in
the spring.

1457
01:23:54,000 --> 01:23:58,000
It'll be good for
you... afterwards.

1458
01:23:58,000 --> 01:24:00,000
After she dies?

1459
01:24:00,000 --> 01:24:03,000
Is that what you mean?

1460
01:24:03,000 --> 01:24:05,000
Move after she dies?

1461
01:24:05,000 --> 01:24:07,000
That's the plan?

1462
01:24:07,000 --> 01:24:10,000
Look... David told me

1463
01:24:10,000 --> 01:24:14,000
that she's only got
a few months left.

1464
01:24:14,000 --> 01:24:16,000
Dianne...

1465
01:24:16,000 --> 01:24:19,000
If David told you
she had ten years left

1466
01:24:19,000 --> 01:24:21,000
would you be here
right now?

1467
01:24:21,000 --> 01:24:22,000
Be honest with me.

1468
01:24:22,000 --> 01:24:23,000
No, you be honest.

1469
01:24:23,000 --> 01:24:24,000
Would you do it again

1470
01:24:24,000 --> 01:24:26,000
knowing the kind of
life she's had...

1471
01:24:26,000 --> 01:24:27,000
with doctors and surgery?

1472
01:24:27,000 --> 01:24:29,000
You don't know anything
about her life.

1473
01:24:29,000 --> 01:24:30,000
She has a friend.

1474
01:24:30,000 --> 01:24:32,000
They tell secrets

1475
01:24:32,000 --> 01:24:35,000
and share ice cream
and sing songs.

1476
01:24:35,000 --> 01:24:36,000
She's dying.

1477
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:38,000
She's not even
six years old

1478
01:24:38,000 --> 01:24:39,000
and she's dying.

1479
01:24:39,000 --> 01:24:41,000
Now, what was the point?

1480
01:24:44,000 --> 01:24:47,000
Look, we're going to
have kids... healthy kids.

1481
01:24:47,000 --> 01:24:49,000
We're going to have
a real family.

1482
01:24:49,000 --> 01:24:51,000
Do you even know
what that is?

1483
01:24:51,000 --> 01:24:54,000
Or do you mean
a "perfect" family

1484
01:24:54,000 --> 01:24:56,000
where no one's ever sick

1485
01:24:56,000 --> 01:24:59,000
or angry or sad
or in pain?

1486
01:24:59,000 --> 01:25:01,000
Six years, Mark...

1487
01:25:01,000 --> 01:25:05,000
you've never even
touched your daughter...

1488
01:25:05,000 --> 01:25:07,000
never even seen her.

1489
01:25:07,000 --> 01:25:08,000
Oh, what are we
talking about?

1490
01:25:08,000 --> 01:25:11,000
I love you, and that's
all that matters now.

1491
01:25:11,000 --> 01:25:14,000
Where were you?

1492
01:25:14,000 --> 01:25:17,000
What were you doing, Mark,
when I was up all night crying

1493
01:25:17,000 --> 01:25:19,000
because I was too tired
to fall asleep?

1494
01:25:19,000 --> 01:25:22,000
Where were you when
I was changing diapers

1495
01:25:22,000 --> 01:25:23,000
or going to the grocery store

1496
01:25:23,000 --> 01:25:25,000
or taking walks
on the beach?

1497
01:25:25,000 --> 01:25:26,000
Where were you?!

1498
01:25:26,000 --> 01:25:28,000
I'm... I'm here now.

1499
01:25:28,000 --> 01:25:30,000
Six years...

1500
01:25:30,000 --> 01:25:34,000
for six years I have been
apologizing for you in my head

1501
01:25:34,000 --> 01:25:36,000
trying to understand

1502
01:25:36,000 --> 01:25:37,000
trying to make excuses

1503
01:25:37,000 --> 01:25:39,000
and... now I understand.

1504
01:25:39,000 --> 01:25:40,000
Understand what?

1505
01:25:40,000 --> 01:25:44,000
Julia is my daughter.

1506
01:25:44,000 --> 01:25:46,000
She is...

1507
01:25:46,000 --> 01:25:49,000
part of who I am

1508
01:25:49,000 --> 01:25:52,000
and who I have become.

1509
01:25:52,000 --> 01:25:54,000
I don't know you.

1510
01:25:55,000 --> 01:25:58,000
And you sure don't know me.

1511
01:26:00,000 --> 01:26:02,000
I want you
to leave us alone.

1512
01:26:07,000 --> 01:26:08,000
Don't come back.

1513
01:26:34,000 --> 01:26:35,000
Hi.

1514
01:26:35,000 --> 01:26:36,000
Hey.

1515
01:26:38,000 --> 01:26:40,000
Hannah, can I ask
you a question?

1516
01:26:40,000 --> 01:26:42,000
Sure.

1517
01:26:42,000 --> 01:26:43,000
It's about Julia's dad.
Oh.

1518
01:26:43,000 --> 01:26:45,000
I thought he was coming
to see her.

1519
01:26:45,000 --> 01:26:46,000
Things didn't work out.

1520
01:26:46,000 --> 01:26:47,000
Why not?

1521
01:26:47,000 --> 01:26:50,000
Well, I don't have an answer
to that question...

1522
01:26:50,000 --> 01:26:52,000
not a simple one,
that's for sure.

1523
01:26:52,000 --> 01:26:55,000
But we don't always choose
the right people to love.

1524
01:26:55,000 --> 01:26:56,000
Poets deceive us...

1525
01:26:56,000 --> 01:26:58,000
talk about the feeling

1526
01:26:58,000 --> 01:27:01,000
and things
we say to each other...

1527
01:27:01,000 --> 01:27:03,000
and those things
are important...

1528
01:27:03,000 --> 01:27:06,000
but in the end,
it all comes down

1529
01:27:06,000 --> 01:27:10,000
to how much we're willing
to give of ourselves.

1530
01:27:10,000 --> 01:27:13,000
Like Romeo and Juliet
dying for each other.

1531
01:27:13,000 --> 01:27:15,000
Well, I don't know
if killing yourself

1532
01:27:15,000 --> 01:27:17,000
in a crypt before you check
your girlfriend for a pulse

1533
01:27:17,000 --> 01:27:19,000
is an act of love

1534
01:27:19,000 --> 01:27:20,000
but it makes
for a good story.

1535
01:27:20,000 --> 01:27:23,000
Love isn't always
so dramatic...

1536
01:27:23,000 --> 01:27:26,000
but it is an adventure.

1537
01:27:26,000 --> 01:27:28,000
( kissing sounds )

1538
01:27:28,000 --> 01:27:30,000
( chuckling )

1539
01:27:35,000 --> 01:27:36,000
I just spoke
to Tess Williams.

1540
01:27:36,000 --> 01:27:37,000
She's coming home tomorrow.

1541
01:27:37,000 --> 01:27:39,000
Oh, good.

1542
01:27:39,000 --> 01:27:40,000
Where's Amy?

1543
01:27:40,000 --> 01:27:41,000
Oh, she rode her
bike into town.

1544
01:27:41,000 --> 01:27:43,000
Oh.

1545
01:27:43,000 --> 01:27:45,000
You think Tess knows
the Dewey decimal system?

1546
01:27:45,000 --> 01:27:46,000
I bet she could learn.

1547
01:27:46,000 --> 01:27:47,000
Mmm.

1548
01:27:47,000 --> 01:27:49,000
Why, are you going
to get her a job?

1549
01:27:49,000 --> 01:27:50,000
Well, I can try.

1550
01:27:50,000 --> 01:27:52,000
David and I
were talking about it.

1551
01:27:52,000 --> 01:27:53,000
He thinks
he may know a doctor

1552
01:27:53,000 --> 01:27:54,000
who needs a receptionist.

1553
01:27:54,000 --> 01:27:55,000
How is David?

1554
01:27:55,000 --> 01:27:58,000
Well, I invited him to dinner

1555
01:27:58,000 --> 01:28:00,000
but he took a rain check.

1556
01:28:00,000 --> 01:28:03,000
You know
he's selling his house?

1557
01:28:03,000 --> 01:28:05,000
Where's he going to live?

1558
01:28:05,000 --> 01:28:07,000
I saw his sign
on my way back from the market.

1559
01:28:07,000 --> 01:28:09,000
Hmm.

1560
01:28:09,000 --> 01:28:11,000
Well, maybe he's getting
a bigger place.

1561
01:28:11,000 --> 01:28:12,000
Is he seeing anybody?

1562
01:28:12,000 --> 01:28:14,000
Don't ask me.

1563
01:28:14,000 --> 01:28:15,000
Ask him.

1564
01:28:15,000 --> 01:28:19,000
Oh, stop avoiding him,
Di, it's silly.

1565
01:28:19,000 --> 01:28:20,000
He cares about you.

1566
01:28:20,000 --> 01:28:21,000
He always has.

1567
01:28:21,000 --> 01:28:23,000
I know, and I didn't
treat him very well.

1568
01:28:23,000 --> 01:28:24,000
I carried a torch for Mark

1569
01:28:24,000 --> 01:28:26,000
and David got tired
of being patient.

1570
01:28:26,000 --> 01:28:28,000
Why do you think
he's not coming to dinner?

1571
01:28:28,000 --> 01:28:30,000
Well, maybe because
I invited him, not you.

1572
01:28:30,000 --> 01:28:33,000
Or maybe it's because
he's seeing somebody.

1573
01:28:33,000 --> 01:28:34,000
No...

1574
01:28:34,000 --> 01:28:36,000
it's just better
that I stay away from him.

1575
01:28:36,000 --> 01:28:38,000
All I ever gave David
was a hard time.

1576
01:28:38,000 --> 01:28:41,000
Tomorrow's another day,
Scarlett.

1577
01:28:41,000 --> 01:28:43,000
She blew her chance.

1578
01:28:58,000 --> 01:29:00,000
Amy!

1579
01:29:00,000 --> 01:29:02,000
She's here.

1580
01:29:04,000 --> 01:29:06,000
Mom!

1581
01:29:06,000 --> 01:29:07,000
Oh, Amy!

1582
01:29:07,000 --> 01:29:09,000
I missed you so much.

1583
01:29:09,000 --> 01:29:11,000
Oh!

1584
01:29:11,000 --> 01:29:13,000
Let me look at you.

1585
01:29:13,000 --> 01:29:15,000
You look great.

1586
01:29:15,000 --> 01:29:18,000
A lot better than
I used to, right?

1587
01:29:18,000 --> 01:29:20,000
I feel better, too.

1588
01:29:20,000 --> 01:29:22,000
I'm not perfect,
you know.

1589
01:29:22,000 --> 01:29:24,000
You don't go in
and come out

1590
01:29:24,000 --> 01:29:26,000
and that's it.

1591
01:29:26,000 --> 01:29:28,000
I've got
to go to meetings

1592
01:29:28,000 --> 01:29:31,000
and... and get
lots of exercise

1593
01:29:31,000 --> 01:29:33,000
and I've got
to eat right.

1594
01:29:33,000 --> 01:29:35,000
Can't sit around
and get sad.

1595
01:29:35,000 --> 01:29:37,000
I got to get a job.

1596
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:45,000
Oh, Amy, I almost lost you.

1597
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:48,000
I'm so sorry.

1598
01:29:48,000 --> 01:29:49,000
Would you forgive me?

1599
01:29:49,000 --> 01:29:52,000
Mom, I can
exercise with you.

1600
01:29:52,000 --> 01:29:53,000
We'll go on walks

1601
01:29:53,000 --> 01:29:55,000
and I'll jog
if you want.

1602
01:29:55,000 --> 01:29:57,000
That would be great.

1603
01:29:57,000 --> 01:29:58,000
I would love that.

1604
01:29:58,000 --> 01:30:00,000
You and me,
we're going to make it

1605
01:30:00,000 --> 01:30:02,000
right?

1606
01:30:02,000 --> 01:30:03,000
Right.

1607
01:30:07,000 --> 01:30:10,000
And we can talk about Dad.

1608
01:30:10,000 --> 01:30:13,000
I'm a lot braver now.

1609
01:30:17,000 --> 01:30:19,000
I'm going home
with my mom now

1610
01:30:19,000 --> 01:30:21,000
but I'll be back
to play, okay?

1611
01:30:21,000 --> 01:30:23,000
Not in the morning,
because school's starting.

1612
01:30:23,000 --> 01:30:26,000
But after school,
sometimes

1613
01:30:26,000 --> 01:30:29,000
if I don't have
too much homework.

1614
01:30:29,000 --> 01:30:32,000
And every Sunday
with my mom for pancakes.

1615
01:30:32,000 --> 01:30:34,000
Mee...

1616
01:30:36,000 --> 01:30:38,000
Bye.

1617
01:30:41,000 --> 01:30:43,000
Well, it's just you
and me now, kiddo.

1618
01:30:46,000 --> 01:30:48,000
But you know what?

1619
01:30:48,000 --> 01:30:53,000
We're still going to have fun,
just like we always have.

1620
01:30:53,000 --> 01:30:57,000
We'll swim
and we'll take our walks

1621
01:30:57,000 --> 01:31:02,000
and we'll sing
and we'll read stories...

1622
01:31:02,000 --> 01:31:06,000
Maybe we'll pick out some new
wallpaper for your room, hmm?

1623
01:31:06,000 --> 01:31:09,000
I wouldn't trade one minute
we've had together.

1624
01:31:09,000 --> 01:31:12,000
Not for all the tea in China.

1625
01:31:12,000 --> 01:31:16,000
Do you know how much tea
there is in China?

1626
01:31:19,000 --> 01:31:20,000
Oh.

1627
